VENICE, June 20--Leaders of the seven major non-Communist industrialized nations will open two days of talks tomorrow with two goals uppermost in mind: the restoration of a semblance of unity among themselves and the shaping of policies to deal with Soviet expansionism and with instability in the Middle East.
headline_main: In Venice, Tough Issues of Unity and Aims; 'Shared Goals and Shared Respect' AT VENICE MEETING: KEY ISSUES OF UNITY

abstract: ROME, June 19--President Carter arrived in Italy tonight for a visit during which, he said, he would be totally frank with the leaders from Western Europe, Japan and Canada in seeking "to sustain world opposition to Soviet aggression."

abstract: Con Errico, a 58-year-old former jockey, was sentenced yesterday to 10 years in prison for his part in fixing thoroughbred races at New York tracks during the mid-1970's. Judge Jack B. Weinstein also fined Errico $25,000 in Brooklyn Federal Court and noted that "athletic contests should go only to the swift and the skilled."
headline_main: Errico Gets 10 Years In Race-Fixing Case; Four Months to Appeal Errico Gets 10 Years 'No Room for Fixers' Exotic Betting Involved

abstract: John B. McCauley, who forsook a medical career while studying at Columbia University to go on the Broadway stage as Jack McCauley in a series of musical comedies, died Friday in Menlo Park, Calif. He was 79 years old.
